<subSubSection id="C3546563994B112AFD76FDAFFB70FDAD" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF136E8994B112AFD76FDAFFB70FDAD" blockId="74.[700,1229,193,627]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
ETYMOLOGY: The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D6B994B112AFBD3FDAFFB7EFDE6" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" box="[1148,1229,545,568]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ebenus">
<emphasis id="B93AEAFA994B112AFBD3FDAFFB7EFDE6" box="[1148,1229,545,568]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">ebenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(of ebony, black) is a Latin adjectival. I refer to the integumentary color of these beetles.
</paragraph>
